Working with STIP Compass data in R: An Introduction

David Howoldt and Benjamin Bjerkan-Wade

2024-07-24

This data story provides a basic introduction to working with STIP Compass data. It explains what datasets are made available by the STIP Data Lab, the variables they include, and how to work with them in R. It also highlights the relationship of policy initiatives and instruments and common pitfalls in analysing them. This data story provides first step elements for analysts and researchers to consider when starting to analyse STI policies.

The STIP Compass portal offers a variety of tools to gain insights from the collected data. For those who prefer more control, a custom approach, or need reproducible results, working directly with the dataset can be highly beneficial. The dataset is derived from the STIP Survey, which systematically collects both quantitative and qualitative data on national science, technology, and innovation (STI) policies. This survey covers a broad spectrum of STI policy areas from 59 territories and the EU. This is an introduction to working with the STIP Survey data, providing a step-by-step guide for accessing, understanding and analysing the dataset using R.

Downloading data

Available datasets

The STIP Data Lab makes available several datasets, corresponding to the four survey waves completed since the inception of the STIP Compass in its current form in 2017, as well as datasets resulting from previous data collection activities on STI policies (see the list of datasets here https://stip.oecd.org/stip/pages/stipDataLab). The most recent dataset is the 2023 ‘live database’, comprising all policy initiatives reported in the most recent survey wave and all updates made to that data since then (countries have continuous access to the survey tool also after the conclusion of a survey wave). The ‘live database’ is updated every few months by synchronising the STIP Compass database with the data in an online tool where STIP Survey respondents provide data. For most cases, using the ‘live database’ for analysis is recommended, as it contains the most recent policy data.

Loading the data

An obvious approach to loading a STIP Survey dataset into R is downloading the CSV file made available by the STIP Data Lab and loading it using the base R function ‘read.csv’. However, this can be problematic as using this function can result in truncated rows, meaning that substantial parts of the data are simply not loaded into R. Therefore, we recommend using the ‘fread’ function from the data.table package to ensure the complete dataset is loaded without any data loss. The code below loads some R packages required for the analyses presented later, and loads into R the full ‘live dataset’ using fread directly from the STIP Compass webpage.

if (!requireNamespace("pacman", quietly = TRUE)) {
  install.packages("pacman") # pacman is a package for convenient installing and/or loading of packages and makes it easy for users of this tutorial to run the code from this tutorial on their own machine 
}
pacman::p_load(data.table, dplyr, ggplot2, stringr, tidyr, DT)

# Directly read the dataset from the URL using fread
stip_survey <- fread("https://stip.oecd.org/assets/downloads/STIP_Survey.csv")

For a more focused analysis, it is also possible to manually filter the STIP Survey data based on specific parameters such as policy instruments, themes and target groups prior to downloading. This can be done on the STIP Data Lab download page, where users can customize the dataset according to their needs and then export it as a CSV or XLSX here.

Variables in the dataset

The ‘live dataset’ comprises more than 10,000 rows and more than 800 columns. The columns fall into four groups; further context can be found in the publicly available survey data model. For each survey wave, the data model is slightly updated.

  • Policy initatives: The leftmost columns provide information on policy initiatives, the STIP Survey’s main unit of reporting, and correspond to the ‘policy initiative fiche’ described in the data model. They contain qualitative as well as quantitative information.

  • Themes: A set of columns with names starting with “TH”. These are dummy columns indicating membership of policy initiatives with different themes. The current STIP Survey has 58 themes, which correspond to the different questions addressed to survey respondents. Policy initiatives are linked to one or more themes.

  • Target groups: A set of columns with names starting with “TG”. These are dummy columns indicating the direct beneficiaries (or ‘Target Groups’) of policy initiatives. The current STIP Survey specifies 33 types of direct beneficiaries. Policy initiatives have one or more direct beneficiaries.

  • Policy instruments: The remaining columns describe the policy instruments associated with policy initiatives. The data model comprises 28 instrument types, denoted in the ‘InstrumentTypeLabel’ column. All columns starting with letter F followed by a number describe instrument facets as specified in the data model. There are more than 600 columns of this type, and analysts mainly interested in policy initiatives might disregard their content.

  • Coding schemes: The data model specifies that policy themes, direct beneficiaries and policy instruments are organised using two-level coding schemes, with smaller sets of broad categories at the first level, and more specific instances under these categories at the second level. The dataset only provides information on the second, more granular level. The first row of the dataset below the header contains additional detail on the content of columns, rather than observational data. It helps understanding the links between the dataset and the data model. Using this information and the data model, analysts can easily infer the broader category for each observation in the dataset.

#To facilitate working with the dataset, we generate a separate 'Codebook' dataframe listing the column names and the detail given in the first row, for variables on themes and direct beneficiaries
codebook <- cbind(names(stip_survey), as.character(stip_survey[1,])) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  filter(str_detect(V1, "TH|TG")) 

names(codebook) <- c("Code","Meaning")

#Next, we clean up the dataset by removing the first row, so that all rows in the dataset now contain survey data.  
stip_survey <- stip_survey[-1,]

#We also convert dummy columns on policy themes and direct beneficiaries to numeric format (given the first row of the dataset containing text information, columns had character formatting before).
stip_survey <- stip_survey %>%
    mutate(across(starts_with(c("TH","TG")), as.numeric))

Policy initiatives and policy instruments

In the STIP Survey, policy initiatives are defined as a public action that:

  1. Aims to achieve one or several public policy goals in the policy area of science, technology and innovation.

  2. Is expected to modify or frame the behaviour of actors and stakeholders, being national, domestic or foreign, who are part of or influential on, the national innovation system, and

  3. Is implemented with a minimum time horizon or on a continuous basis (i.e. not as a one-off “event”).

The first column of the dataset provides the IDs of initiatives. They are written as Unique Resource Identifiers, with the actual ID of each initiative denoted by a string of numbers following the final backslash. Free text fields provide information about the names of initiatives, short descriptions, and objectives. Budget information and the names of the organisations responsible for the implementation of initiatives are also provided.

Policy instruments, on the other hand, are the tools and mechanisms used to implement policy initiatives. For the 28 instrument types included in the dataset, the column ‘InstrumentTypeLabel’ indicates the type of each dataset. The data model specifies as broad instrument categories: Governance; Direct financial support; Indirect financial support; Collaborative infrastructures (soft and physical); and Guidance, regulation and incentives.

A policy initiative can have one or more policy instruments. Importantly, rows in the dataset correspond to individual policy instruments. If an initiative comes with more than one policy instrument, it occupies several rows in the dataset, with the initiative-level information being repeated across these rows, and distinct instrument information in each row.

Duplicated rows? Avoid this pitfall!

A common pitfall in the analysis of the STIP Survey dataset is that the number of policy instruments is mistaken for the number of policy initiatives. To obtain the number of policy initiatives in the dataset or a subset of the data, analysts need to ensure they only count rows with unique policy initiatives. In R, functions such as ‘duplicated’, ‘unique’, ‘dplyr::distinct’, or ‘dplyr::group_by’ can be helpful to ensure that initiatives are counted correctly. The following code snippet demonstrates how to remove rows duplicating initiative data. The resulting dataset comprises strictly one row per policy initiative. Note that for policy initiatives with more than one policy instrument, only information on one policy instrument is retained. The resulting dataset can be useful for analysing policy initiatives, but it does not provide accurate information on policy instruments.

stip_survey_Unique <- stip_survey[!duplicated(InitiativeID)]

Policy themes and direct beneficiaries

For both policy themes and direct beneficiaries, the second level of coding is provided in the dataset analysed here, whereas the broad thematic areas/groups can be inferred from the data model referred to above.

The 58 policy themes in the dataset fall into seven broad thematic areas described in the data model: Governance; Public research system; Innovation in firms and innovative entrepreneurship; Knowledge exchange and co-creation; Human resources for research and innovation; Research and innovation for society; and Net zero transitions.

The 33 types of direct beneficiaries in the dataset direct beneficiaries, fall into eight broader groups described in the data model: Research and education organisations; Researchers, students and teachers; Firms by size; Firms by age; Intermediaries; Governmental entities; Economic actors (individuals); and Social groups especially emphasised.

To give an example of a theme-based analysis of the dataset, we turn to policy initiatives concerned with the financing of innovation in firms. The STIP Survey contains four themes relevant in this context that can easily identified in the codebook: Financial support to business R&D and innovation; Non-financial support to business R&D and innovation; Foreign direct investment; and Access to finance for innovation. The direct beneficiaries of policy initiatives could be analysed in a similar way.

financing_innovation <- stip_survey %>%
  dplyr::select(!starts_with("F")) %>% #just removing columns not needed for present analysis to make the dataset easier to handle
 filter((TH31 + TH32 + TH36 + TH38) > 0) %>% #filter to retain only the policy themes in question
  pivot_longer(c(TH31, TH32, TH36, TH38), names_to = "Theme") %>% #change the format of the dataframe to enable separate analysis of the four themes
  filter(value == 1) %>%
  group_by(InitiativeID, Theme) %>%
  summarise(n_instruments = n()) %>% #obtain the number of instruments by counting the number of rows per policy initiativer per theme
  ungroup %>%
  group_by(Theme) %>%
  distinct(InitiativeID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% # retain only unique policy initiatives 
  summarise(n_initiatives = n(), n_instruments = sum(n_instruments)) # count unique policy initiatives and sum the numbers of their instruments

The figure below shows that there are more policy instruments than initiatives for each theme; this is a reflection of the data set, as each policy initiative comes with one or several policy instruments. The analysis also shows that the ratio of policy instruments and initiatives varies. For some themes, there are markedly more instruments than initiatives, while for others, the number of instruments does not exceed the number of policy initiatives by much. This indicates that the choice of policy instruments implementing a policy initiative varies depending on their theme.

TH32_instruments <- stip_survey %>%
  dplyr::select(!starts_with("F")) %>%
  filter(TH32 > 0) %>%
  group_by(InstrumentTypeLabel) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  top_n(5)

Taking a closer look, the figure below maps the policy instruments supporting the implementation of policy initiatives linked to the theme ‘Non-financial support to business R&D and innovation’. It plausibly shows that instrument types related to advisory services and networking and collaboration are most prominent among these initiatives. The presence of an instrument type about grants for business R&D and innovation suggests that policy initiatives under this theme might at the same time also provide financial support for business R&D. This is not surprising as policy initiatives often span several themes at the same time.

Conclusion

This data story has provided an introduction to using STIP Survey data with R, from downloading the dataset to explaining its structure and contents and to presenting basic steps for its analysis. These should serve as initial steps into analysing the wealth of data available in STIP Compass. Working directly with the dataset can be highly beneficial, especially for users who prefer more control, a custom approach, or need reproducible results. As highlighted, data users should be cautious with regard to the structure of the dataset and be mindful of the differences between policy initiatives and policy instruments when analysing the dataset.

This story is linked to another data story introducing an analysis of text data describing policy initiatives from the STIP Survey dataset: Getting Started with NLP of Research and Innovation Policy Data using R. The STIP Compass team strives to support users of the survey data sets and will develop more useful guidance materials for data users and analysts in the future.
